Data Description:¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Domain:¶

Banking

Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Attribute Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any.
  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account: Doesthe customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Doesthe customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Preparing the data to train a model
  • Training and making predictions using a classificationmodel
  • Model evaluation

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Observations from the five point summary and above data information.¶

  • No null values are present.
  • Most of the data types are integer, except CCAvg is float.
  • Columns 'ID' and 'ZIP codes' can be ignored as they would be unique for each observations. It would not add any values to model.
  • 'Securities Account', 'CD Account', 'Online' and 'CreditCard' are having categorical values such as 0 or 1. They might impact the Outcome 'Personal loan'.
  • 'Age', 'Experience', 'Income', 'Family', 'CCAvg', 'Mortgage' would highly impact teh 'Personal Loan' attribute.
  • 'Education' is is also having categorical values and may impact the 'Personal Loan'.
  • As Dependent variable 'Personal Loan' is having categorical values, we will use Logistic regression modeling.
  • However, there are some imputations needed for 'Experience' column. The above analysis shows the minimum value as -3.

    sns.countplot(ax=axs[1],x=independent,data=dataset)

Treat negative experiences¶

In [26]:
# Treat the negative values as per ranges. We can not replace all values as mean because lowest age 23 cannot have experience 20 years.
dataset_modified = dataset.copy()
# User bins to do the intervals and then do the average of it and assign negative values to the average of that group.
# Take interval of 5's. minimum age 23, maximum age 67
bin_interval = [22, 27, 32, 37, 42, 47, 52, 57, 62, 68]
labels=['A', 'B', 'C','D', 'E', 'F','G','H', 'I']

dataset_modified['Age_bins'] = pd.cut(dataset_modified['Age'],bins=bin_interval, labels=labels)
avg=dataset_modified[dataset_modified['Experience']>0].groupby('Age_bins')['Experience'].mean().apply(np.ceil)
for x in dataset_modified[dataset_modified['Experience']<0].itertuples():
    dataset_modified.loc[x.Index,'Experience']=avg[x.Age_bins]
dataset_modified.drop('Age_bins',axis=1,inplace=True)
print("Negative Experience count:{0}".format(dataset_modified[dataset_modified['Experience']<0]['Experience'].count()))
dataset_modified.describe().T

Model imporvements:¶

As per out LogisticRegression model above, we used parameters such as C, penalty, solver to configure the model building. We can play with these values and check which turns out to be the best for our case.

Output Analysis:¶

  • As described above, looking at confusion matrix we can learn the number of TP, TN, FP, FN. As we are trying to build model that can predict the Personal loan success rate, we need to focus on our type II error. False Negative is 55. This means we predicted that the people want apply for Personal loan but they end up taking it. We missed the business opportunity there. Ideally, out model should be predicted all situation right or we should have 0 FP and 0 FP. For out business model we need to have smallest number of type II error.

Parameters descriptions:¶

penalty{‘l1’, ‘l2’, ‘elasticnet’, ‘none’}, default=’l2’¶
  • Used to specify the norm used in the penalization. The newton-cg, sag and lbfgs solvers support only l2 penalties. elasticnet is only supported by the saga solver. If none (not supported by the liblinear solver), no regularization is applied.
dualbool, default=False¶
  • Dual formulation is only implemented for l2 penalty with liblinear solver. Prefer dual=False when n_samples > n_features.
tolfloat, default=1e-4¶
  • Tolerance for stopping criteria.
Cfloat, default=1.0¶
  • Inverse of regularization strength
fit_interceptbool, default=True¶
  • Specifies if a constant (a.k.a. bias or intercept) should be added to the decision function.
intercept_scalingfloat, default=1¶
  • Useful only when the solver liblinear is used and self.fit_intercept is set to True.
class_weightdict or ‘balanced’, default=None¶
  • Weights associated with classes in the form {class_label: weight}. If not given, all classes are supposed to have weight one.
random_stateint, RandomState instance, default=None¶
  • Used when solver == sag, saga or liblinear to shuffle the data.
solver{‘newton-cg’, ‘lbfgs’, ‘liblinear’, ‘sag’, ‘saga’}, default=’lbfgs’¶
  • Algorithm to use in the optimization problem. For small datasets, liblinear is a good choice, whereas sag and saga are faster for large ones. liblinear looks much better for our case of Personal Loan.
  • newton-cg, lbfgs, sag and saga handle L2 or no penalty
  • liblinear and saga also handle L1 penalty
  • saga also supports elasticnet penalty
  • liblinear does not support setting penalty='none'
max_iterint, default=100¶
  • Maximum number of iterations taken for the solvers to converge.
multi_class{‘auto’, ‘ovr’, ‘multinomial’}, default=’auto’¶
  • If the option chosen is ovr, then a binary problem is fit for each label
verboseint, default=0¶
  • For the liblinear and lbfgs solvers set verbose to any positive number for verbosity.
warm_startbool, default=False¶

When set to True, reuse the solution of the previous call to fit as initialization, otherwise, just erase the previous solution. Useless for liblinear solver.

n_jobsint, default=None¶
  • Number of CPU cores used when parallelizing over classes if multi_class=ovr. This parameter is ignored when the solver is set to liblinear regardless of whether multi_class is specified or not.
l1_ratiofloat, default=None¶
  • The Elastic-Net mixing parameter, with 0 <= l1_ratio <= 1. Only used if penalty='elasticnet'.
Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html¶

# Function that can test multiple solvers with multiple C values and other params we got above.

column_params_types = [('solver', str), 
             ('penalty', str), 
             ('multi_class', str), 
             ('dual', bool), 
             ('fit_intercept', bool), 
             ('class_weight', str), 
             ('C', np.float128), 
             ('train score', np.float128), ('test score', np.float128), 
             ('recall score', np.float128), 
             ('precision score', np.float128), 
             ('roc auc score', np.float128)]

# Lets create dataframes one with type and one without.
dataset_compare_type = pd.DataFrame({x: pd.Series(dtype=y) for x, y in column_params_types})
#initialize params
idx = 0
rows_list = []

def all_params_regression():
    
    # Initialize defaults first
    train_accuracy = 0.0
    # Test
    test_accuracy = 0.0
    test_rscore = 0.0
    test_pscore = 0.0
    test_auc = 0.0
    
    # Vars
    global idx
    global rows_list

    global dataset_compare_type
    
    C = [0.01,0.1,0.25,0.5,0.75,1]
    solver = ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'sag', 'saga']
    penalties = ['l1', 'l2', 'elasticnet', 'none']
    multi_class = ['ovr', 'multinomial', 'auto']
    cweight = ['balanced', None]
    dual = [True, False]
    fit_intercept = [True, False]
    
    for s in solver:
        for p in penalties:
            for mc in multi_class:
                for d in dual:
                    for fit in fit_intercept:
                        for cw in cweight:
                            for c in C:
                                logreg_fn = LogisticRegression(solver=s, 
                                                            max_iter=1000, 
                                                            penalty=p, 
                                                            dual=d, 
                                                            fit_intercept=fit, 
                                                            class_weight=cw,
                                                            C=c, 
                                                            random_state=42)

                                if s == 'newton-cg' and p not in ('l2', 'none'):
                                    continue

                                if s == 'newton-cg' and d == True:
                                    continue

                                if s == 'lbfgs' and p not in ('l2', 'none'):
                                    continue

                                if s == 'lbfgs' and d == True:
                                    continue

                                if p == 'l1' and d == True:
                                    continue

                                if s != 'saga' and p == 'elasticnet':
                                    continue

                                if s == 'liblinear' and p == 'none':
                                    continue

                                if s == 'sag' and p not in ('l2', 'none'):
                                    continue

                                if s == 'sag' and d == True:
                                    continue

                                if s == 'saga' and d == True:
                                    continue

                                if s == 'saga' and p == 'elasticnet' and d == False:
                                    continue

                                logreg_fn.fit(X_train, y_train)

                                logreg_score_train = logreg_fn.score(X_train, y_train)

                                logreg_score_test = logreg_fn.score(X_test, y_test)
                                
                                y_predict = logreg.predict(X_test)
                                
                                rscore = recall_score(y_test,y_predict)
                                
                                pscore = precision_score(y_test,y_predict)
                                
                                f1 = f1_score(y_test,y_predict)
                                
                                roc = roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict)
                                
                                data_modified = {'solver':s, 
                                                 'penalty': p,
                                                 'multi_class': mc,
                                                 'dual': d, 
                                                 'fit_intercept': fit,
                                                 'class_weight': cw, 'C':c, 
                                                 'train score': logreg_score_train, 
                                                 'test score': logreg_score_test, 
                                                 'recall score': rscore, 
                                                 'precision score': pscore, 
                                                 'roc auc score': roc} 
                                
                                # 
                                # Choose highest accuracy model
                                # 
                                if (logreg_score_test >= test_accuracy and logreg_score_train >= train_accuracy):
                                    train_accuracy = logreg_score_train
                                    test_accuracy = logreg_score_test
                                    test_rscore = rscore
                                    test_pscore = pscore
                                    test_auc = roc
                                    dataset_compare_type = dataset_compare_type.append([data_modified], ignore_index=True)
                                
                                
all_params_regression()

Business Understanding:¶

  • As we know, here the Thera bank is asking for the Machine learning solution based on the past data to convert it's liability customers to the Personal loan applicants. To do that, they would like to identify the right customers or we can say potential candidates who can apply for the Personal loan. Also, bank would like to spend their marketing money wisely and such that maximum people gets approved for Personal loan and bank won't waste money.

  • Based on our above final model, our accuracy for the model is around 96%, which is very high. For us, not just accuracy but recall and precision plays equal amount of role in it. We would like to reduce type II error in this case. False Negative plays crucial role. It means we predicted the audience who won'r buy personal loan but they end up buying personal loan. This number should be as small as possible so that Bank would get enough business. We can see the values for these parametes from the above confusion matrix.

    • TP: 98
    • TN: 1342
    • FP: 6
    • FN: 54
  • Also, I would like to call out the best audience to reach out for the marketing from above visualizations. Bank should target people with higher family size, higher income, higher credit card spendings. They tend to apply for Personal loan more often from the rest of the combinations.
  • Hence proved!
